com.fedex.api
Class WebAPIMessageParser

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--com.fedex.api.WebAPIMessageParser
public class WebAPIMessageParser
extends java.lang.Object

This class can be used directly by a client program to create CTS request strings for the FedEx Ship Manager API, send them, and parse the responses. It is also used by the API Transaction Classes, which provide another level of abstraction from the underlying CTS message format.

To create and process a request, specify the appropriate CTS transaction type and its UTI in the 'request' constructor. Add tag/value pairs with the put methods. Call the process method. Then use the get methods to retrieve the values for individual tags. This class can also be used to create a request that is to be sent by other means than the process method. Add tag/value pairs with the put methods, but then call the getRequest method to get the CTS request to be sent. After receiving a CTS response, pass it into one of the 'response' constructors, and then use the get methods to retrieve the values for the desired tags.

Provides the necessary information (Host IP address, host port, and read time-out value) for establishing a communications link with ATOM. Also sets the API's maximum reply buffer length.
This static method must be called prior to processing FedEx services. This method may only be called once in a process. The host, port and readTimeout can be changed if desired with the reinitialize method.

Parameters:

port - port number of ATOM

get

public byte[] get(java.lang.String tag,
                  short offset)
Retrieves the [offset+1]th element of the one-dimensional array of values of the given tag from the response. Equivalent to calling get(String, short[]) with short[] of length 1. For example, given TRACKING_NUMBER and 0, it returns the first tracking number. To retrieve all tracking numbers from a track by reference response, you could do something like this: 
            // Determine how many tracking numbers the response contains (since the
            // tracking response does not include a count).
            short count = parser.getArraySize(Tags.TRACKING_NUMBER, new short[] {});
            
            // Create an array to receive the tracking numbers.
            byte[][] trackingNumbers = new byte[count][];
            
            // Get all the tracking numbers.
            for (short x = 0; x < count; x++)
            {
                trackingNumbers[x] = parser.get(Tags.TRACKING_NUMBER, x);
                if (trackingNumbers[x] == null)
                    break;
            }

get

public byte[] get(java.lang.String tag,
                  short[] offsets)
Retrieves an element of the multi-dimensional array of values of the given tag from the response. If there were a two-dimensional array FOO_BAR, consisting of an array of foos, each having its own related array of bars, then to retrieve all bars of all foos from a response, you could do something like this: 
            // Find out out many foos we have.
            short foo_count = parser.getArraySize(Tags.FOO_BAR, new short[] {});
            
            // Create a 2-D array of byte arrays in which to store
            // all the bars of all the foos.
            byte[][][] foobars = new byte[foo_count][][];
            
            // Loop over foos.
            for (short x = 0; x < foo_count; x++)
            {
                // Find out how many bars there are for this foo.
                short bar_count = parser.getArraySize(Tags.BAR_COUNT, new short[] {x});
                
                // Create a 1-D array of byte arrays in which to store
                // the bars for this foo.
                foobars[x] = new byte[bar_count][];
                
                // Retrieve the bars for this foo.
                for (short y = 0; y < bar_count; y++)
                {
                    foobars[x][y] = parser.get(Tags.FOO_BAR, new short[] {x, y});
                }
            }

getArraySize

public short getArraySize(java.lang.String tag)
Returns the size (the offset of the element with the highest offset, plus one) of the 1-D array whose tag is given as the first argument. If there are gaps (missing elements with offsets lower than the highest), the value returned will still be the highest offset plus one. Note that the array specified may be an array of arrays, in which case this method still returns the number of elements (subarrays) in it. Calling this function is equivalent to calling getArraySize(String, short[]) with an empty array of shorts as the second argument. If ISO-8859-1 encoding is not supported, returns zero.

getArraySize

public short getArraySize(java.lang.String tag,
                          short offset)
Returns the size of the 1-D array (the offset of the element with the highest offset, plus one) at the given location (as specified by the second argument) in the array whose tag is given in the first argument. Note that the array specified may be an array of arrays, in which case this method still returns the number of elements (subarrays) in it. If there are gaps (missing elements with offsets lower than the highest), the value returned will still be the highest offset plus one. Calling this function is equivalent to calling getArraySize(String, short[]) with one element in array of shorts passed as the second argument. If ISO-8859-1 encoding is not supported, returns zero.

getRequest

public byte[] getRequest()
Gets the request as an array of bytes. If you intend to call the FedEx Ship Manager API directly, or to create your own API for communicating requests to the API Gateway, you can use this method to retrieve the request after completing your set calls. If you intend to use the process method, you should not need to call this one. If ISO-8859-1 encoding is not supported, returns null.

Builds and sends the request via the FedEx Ship Manager API, and parses the reply. Should be called after completing your set() calls. After it returns, you can do your get() calls. You should not call this method if you intend to send your request by calling the API directly from your code, or using your own custom API.
